{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488834"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:59:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:59:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"554"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/554"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.18,0.19,0.5,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"554"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115993"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/554"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"554"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97988"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"459"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"1261"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15459"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49639"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115993"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 52-year-old man presents with a three month history of dyspepsia. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history and drinks two glasses of wine a day. He does not take any medications. The physical examination is unremarkable. He undergoes a gastroscopy and found to have a large 30mm gastric ulcer with an irregular, raised edge on the lesser curve of the stomach. The ulcer is biopsied and chronic inflammatory tissue identified. A rapid urease test is positive. He is started on triple therapy (esomeprazole and two antibiotics). When reviewed four weeks later, his symptoms have significantly improved.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following options is the most important management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stop drug treatment and arrange a three month follow-up","Stop antibiotics and continue esomeprazole","Repeat endoscopy","Urea breath test","Helicobacter pylori serology"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven this gastric ulcer had several concerning features on endoscopy (large size, irregular margins), the most important action is a \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E to check for ulcer healing and exclude a gastric malignancy. Even though the initial biopsies showed benign changes only, insufficient sampling and false negatives are possible. It is important to check that the ulcer has healed - and if not, to repeat the biopsies to exclude malignancy. Unlike duodenal ulcers, the possibility of malignancy and the need for repeat endoscopy should be considered for all gastric ulcers, although in some patients with very low risk features a repeat endoscopy may not be required. A repeat rapid urease test can also be performed at the time of endoscopy to confirm Helicobacter pylori eradication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eurea breath test\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-invasive test that can be performed to confirm the eradication of Helicobacter pylori. All patients who are diagnosed with Helicobacter pylori infection should undergo follow-up testing to confirm eradication, and a urea breath test would be an appropriate option if the patient was not requiring further endoscopic evaluation. In this scenario, endoscopy to confirm ulcer healing and excluding malignancy is most important, and a rapid urease test can be performed at the same time. Note, a rapid urease test is different to a urea breath test and can only be performed at the time of endoscopy whereas a urea breath test is non-invasive however can only be performed after 4 weeks after ceasing antibiotics in order to be performed accurately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt four weeks, even if the infection had been eradicated, \u003Cstrong\u003Eserology\u003C/strong\u003E would still be positive as H. pylori serology can be positive for months to years, and thus this investigation would be of no value to confirm eradication. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt this stage, if the patient\u0027s symptoms have improved with treatment, there is no need to keep him on the \u003Cstrong\u003Eesomeprazole or antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E. Instead, a decision of whether further treatment is needed would be made upon repeat testing to confirm eradication (either rapid urease test at repeat endoscopy if indicated or urea breath test) if they indicated treatment failure due to rising antibiotic resistance. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Malignancy must always be considered in cases of gastric ulcers"],"references":["Lanas A, Chan FKL. Peptic ulcer disease. Lancet 2017; 390: 613-24.","ASGE Standards of Practice Committee, Banerjee S, Cash BD, et al. The role of endoscopy in the management of patients with peptic ulcer disease. Gastrointest Endosc. 2010;71(4):663-668. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gie.2009.11.026"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97988"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"554"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97988"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T08:02:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T08:02:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{